				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} p_{\text {real}} = (1 - p) \times 100 . \end{aligned}$$\end{document}Here, preal=100%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {real}}=100\%$$\end{document} would suggest that the wave motion present in the original time series is real, since no (i.e., p=0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p=0$$\end{document}) randomized time series provided similar (or greater) Fourier power. Contrarily, preal=0%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {real}}=0\%$$\end{document} would indicate a real (i.e., statistically significant) power deficit at that frequency, since all (i.e., p=1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p=1$$\end{document}) randomized time series provided higher Fourier power at that specific frequency. Finally, a value of preal=50%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$p_{\text {real}} = 50\%$$\end{document} would indicate that the power peak is not due to actual oscillatory motions. A similar approach is to calculate the means and standard deviations of the Fourier power values for each independent frequency corresponding to the randomized time series. This provides a direct estimate of whether the original measured Fourier power is within some number of standard deviations of the mean randomized-data power density. As a result, probability estimations of the detected Fourier peaks can be estimated providing the variances and means of the randomized Fourier power values are independent (i.e., follow a normal distribution; Bell et al. 2018).

If a large number (≥1000\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ge 1000$$\end{document}) of randomized permutations are employed, then the fluctuation probabilities will tend to Gaussian statistics (Linnell Nemec and Nemec 1985; Delouille et al. 2008; Jess et al. 2019). In this case, the confidence level can be obtained using a standardized Gaussian distribution. For many solar applications (e.g., McAteer et al. 2002b, 2003; Andic 2008; Bello González et al. 2009; Stangalini et al. 2012; Dorotovič et al. 2014; Freij et al. 2016; Jafarzadeh et al. 2017d, to name but a few examples), a confidence level of 95% is typically employed as a threshold for reliable wave detection. In this case, 99%≤preal≤100%\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$99\% \le p_{\text {real}} \le 100\%$$\end{document} (or 0.00≤p≤0.01\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$0.00 \le p \le 0.01$$\end{document}) is required to satisfy the desired 95% confidence level.

