Various wave speeds in a flux tube in the lower solar atmosphere, from the hot ‘NC5’ flux tube model put forward by Bruls and Solanki (1993), in combination with the surrounding cool VAL-A atmosphere (Vernazza et al. 1981)

The advantage of the magnetic cylinder model is that it allows for the key plasma parameters, e.g., magnetic field strength and plasma density, to differ inside and outside of the flux tube, allowing us to introduce inhomogeneity in the direction perpendicular to the cylinder axis. In this model, relative to the cylindrical coordinates (r,θ,z)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
