				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m=1$$\end{document} and is azimuthally asymmetric (see the middle and right panels of Fig. 37). The fluting modes are higher order in the azimuthal direction with m≥2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m \ge 2$$\end{document}. A further classification of wave types in a magnetic cylinder is “body” or “surface” modes. A body wave is oscillatory in the radial direction inside the tube and evanescently decaying outside. Because the body wave is oscillatory inside the tube, it has a fundamental mode in the radial direction and also higher radial harmonics. In contrast, a surface wave is evanescent inside and outside of the tube with its maximum amplitude at the boundary between the internal and external plasma. Since it is strictly evanescent inside the tube, the surface mode cannot generate higher radial harmonics.

